Central California Foothills and Coastal Mountains

The Central California Foothills and Coastal Mountains extend almost 30 thousand square miles, stretching from the Pacific Ocean to the Sierra Nevada, almost completely encircling the Central Valley. The region is characterized by its low mountains, known as foothills, but also contains lots of flat areas which are used for agriculture.

This ecoregion is known for its Mediterranean climate with hot, dry summers and cool, moist winters, featuring mostly chaparral and oak woodlands. These woodlands host hundreds of plants/vertebrates and thousands of invertebrates, including inhabitants like the western gray squirrel, dusky-footed woodrat, California ground squirrel, and burrowing owl. Coastal wildlife include herring gulls, bat ray, and California sea lions.

This region is densely populated, containing cities like San Francisco, San Jose, and Monterey, as well as major agricultural areas like Salinas. Notable landmarks and areas include the San Francisco Bay ecosystem, the Diablo Range, and the Salinas Valley.
